These channels are active, bounded, and locally interpretable. They are
not yet promoted to required organism claims because their causal
contribution to task competence has not been fully isolated.

\hypertarget{limitations}{%
\subsection{6. Limitations}\label{limitations}}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Visual benchmark performance is low.} 27--47\% on
  MNIST/FashionMNIST variants is well below specialized continual
  learning methods. This is a real limitation if the goal is task
  performance; it is expected if the goal is demonstrating
  organism-first principles.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Setpoint rewrite evidence is mixed.} The strongest evidence is
  persistence and hidden-memory separation. The aggregate cryptic\_shift
  metric is not uniformly positive.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Port disruption is the weakest lesion class.} The organism
  recovers well from most injury types, but isolated port disruption
  remains the least comfortable recovery story.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Scale is small.} The current organism has 64 cells with
  32-dimensional hidden state. Whether these properties survive scaling
  is an open question.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{No ecology.} The current system is a single organism.
  Multi-organism interaction, competition, and collective behavior are
  future work.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Frontier channels are unproven.} Oscillatory coupling,
  reaction-diffusion, stigmergy, and predictive coding are implemented
  and active, but their causal necessity is not yet established.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{The system was developed with AI assistance.} Architecture
  design, implementation, and debugging were conducted in collaboration
  with Claude (Anthropic). The experimental results are from actual code
  execution, not generated text.
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{discussion}{%
\subsection{7. Discussion}\label{discussion}}

\hypertarget{what-this-demonstrates}{%
\subsubsection{7.1 What this
demonstrates}\label{what-this-demonstrates}}

MorphoBASE v1.3 provides evidence that a computational system organized
around explicit physiology can exhibit properties that are typically
difficult to achieve in standard neural networks:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Repair without retraining}: the organism recovers from diverse
  injuries through its own maintenance dynamics, not through gradient
  descent during recovery
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Competence preservation through body maintenance}: task
  performance survives injury because the body that supports it survives
  injury
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Anatomical memory}: a hidden setpoint scaffold persists
  independently of expressed state and guides repair
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Selective growth}: the system adds resources only when
  physiological need justifies the metabolic cost
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Boundary-local adaptation}: interface changes produce
  localized reorganization, not global disruption
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

These properties are individually achievable through specialized ML
techniques. What is novel is that they emerge together from a single
coherent physiological substrate without benchmark-specific engineering.

\hypertarget{relationship-to-levins-framework}{%
\subsubsection{7.2 Relationship to Levin\textquotesingle s
framework}\label{relationship-to-levins-framework}}

MorphoBASE is a computational exploration of ideas developed in the
biological context by Levin and colleagues. Several correspondences are
intentional:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Multi-scale competency}: individual cells make local
  homeostatic decisions; coordination emerges through coupling, not
  central control
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Bioelectric setpoints}: the Z-memory field serves as an
  anatomical target state analogous to bioelectric prepatterns
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Gap junction-mediated coordination}: the conductance matrix
  modulates inter-cell coupling based on physiological agreement,
  analogous to gap junction gating
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Repair as goal-directed behavior}: recovery is guided by
  stored anatomical memory, not by externally imposed correction
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

MorphoBASE is not a faithful simulation of biological tissue. It is a
computational substrate that takes these organizational principles
seriously and tests whether they produce measurable functional
properties.

\hypertarget{what-this-does-not-demonstrate}{%
\subsubsection{7.3 What this does not
demonstrate}\label{what-this-does-not-demonstrate}}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  This is not a competitive continual learning system. Specialized
  methods substantially outperform it on benchmarks.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  This is not a model of real biological tissue. The correspondences to
  biology are organizational, not mechanistic.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  This does not prove that organism-first design is superior to standard
  ML for practical applications.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  This does not demonstrate multi-scale competency in the full sense
  described by Levin --- v1.3 has one scale of cellular organization,
  not nested hierarchies.
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{future-directions-v1.4}{%
\subsection{8. Future Directions (v1.4)}\label{future-directions-v1.4}}

v1.4 extends the organism with:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Explicit shared genome}: a sparse signed regulatory matrix
  shared by all cells
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Per-cell epigenome}: each cell gates the shared genome with
  its own accessibility mask, enabling specialization without per-cell
  dense matrices
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Dual-track bioelectric state}: slow morphogenetic membrane +
  fast task-relay membrane, preventing fast dynamics from overwriting
  anatomical structure
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Local homeostatic controller}: belief state, prediction error,
  precision, and frustration computation per cell
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Voltage-gated junctions}: gap-junction openness dependent on
  voltage mismatch, stress mismatch, and setpoint agreement
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

These extensions aim to test four organism-level properties motivated by
Levin\textquotesingle s 2026 research:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Goal retargetability}: can the organism adopt a changed target
  and reorganize?
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Boundary management}: can coordinated control be enlarged or
  contracted through junction manipulation?
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Memory reinterpretation}: can stored traces be reused after
  changed context?
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \textbf{Cognitive light cone expansion}: does coordinated scope
  enlarge when coupling and memory support it?
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{availability}{%
\subsection{9. Availability}\label{availability}}

To foster responsible development and collaboration in organism-inspired
computation, the complete codebase, configuration files, and
experimental artifacts are available to verified researchers upon
request. The system is implemented in Python with PyTorch and requires
no specialized hardware. Inquiries for access and potential
collaboration can be directed to the author (vetchj88@gmail.com).

